1. Lycus collaris (DRUMM.).

Just as the Carrion—Crow is a dimorphic form of the Hooded Crow, Lycus· collaris· is a eastern form of the Common Jackdow. This latter has also its well-defined geographica] range. As regards coloration L. collaris differs not only, in having a creamy white half-collar, but the grey colour of the occiput and the neck — especially in the breeding season — is so much suffused with silvery white, that those parts appear nearly quite white. Further the grey colour of the back and abdomen is lighter and still lighter margened with grey. We may suppose that BREHM («Vogelfang») had such a typical L. collaris before him, when he wrote the following: «Monedula daurica.
